        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Top Ligands by Data Coverage\n\n| Ligand | ligand_id | VLM Measurements |\n|--------|-----------|-----------------|\n| Glycine | ligand_5760 | 428 |\n| L-Histidine | ligand_5898 | 250 |\n| EDDA | ligand_5975 | 198 |\n| L-Aspartic acid | ligand_5802 | 174 |\n| L-Alanine | ligand_5761 | 159 |\n| Glyphosate | ligand_5937 | 146 |\n| L-Serine | ligand_5828 | 139 |\n| L-Phenylalanine | ligand_5777 | 138 |\n| L-Cysteine | ligand_5856 | 134 |\n\nThe class extends well beyond the 20 standard proteinogenic amino acids to include β-amino acids, N-substituted derivatives, halogenated variants, phosphorylated amino acids, and amino acid-based chelators like EDDA and EDDS. Notably, 100% of the ligands contain a carboxyl group, and 57% feature a primary amine — consistent with the defining α-amino acid motif.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
